{
  "doc_id": "21744",
  "text": "T he papillomavirus E2 protein controls transcription of viral early gene products by binding to specific DNA motifs (ACCN6GGT) critically placed within the viral genome [CITATION_1] . While viral gene expression is controlled by a variety of cellular transcription factors, including TFIID, Sp1, Oct1, and AP1 (2-6), expression of E2 results in increased transcriptional activation from the bovine papillomavirus (BPV) promoter and enhancer elements containing E2 binding sites [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . DNA binding activity is conferred by the C-terminal DNA binding domain (DBD); however, the N-terminal transactivation domain (TAD) of E2 is also necessary for specific activity [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . The ability of the TAD to activate transcription in the absence of the DBD [CITATION_8] indicates that its function is at least partly mediated through complex formation with cellular factors [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] .",
